I gave an AI real permission to post to our team's Slack. Then I built three checks into how it uses that permission. When I finally audited my own logs, one of the three had never actually fired.
TL;DR: "It worked" and "I can verify what it did" are two different claims about an AI action. I built 3 checks into my workflow to close that gap. One of them turned out to have zero logged uses — and the trace I use to explain another one doesn't end the way I first described it, either.
The AI's Slack access runs through MCP tools, and one of the first problems I hit had nothing to do with the message content — it was the channel ID. A channel ID is a machine-readable string. It's exactly the kind of identifier an AI can use correctly and a human can't sanity-check by glancing at it. So the first check I put in place was simple: before the AI uses a channel ID for anything, make it get there through slack_search_channels — a name search, not a raw ID lookup. That turns a step nobody can eyeball into a step a human can.
